00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,412
speech.

2
00:00:00,472 --> 00:00:18,086
Text-to-speech is basically you take a piece of text, like this one, modern text-to-speech synthesis, pipelines typically involved, blah, blah, blah, and you want to make a model that takes this and outputs sound waves as if a human would say it, right?

3
00:00:18,106 --> 00:00:23,035
So either modern text to speech and so on.

4
00:00:23,015 --> 00:00:25,558
Now, I have multiple problems when doing this.

5
00:00:27,359 --> 00:00:30,743
First of all, the text here is words.

6
00:00:30,803 --> 00:00:33,205
Let's say we can tokenize the text into words.

7
00:00:33,665 --> 00:00:36,348
So you have modern text to speech.

8
00:00:36,708 --> 00:00:37,669
Those are four tokens.

9
00:00:37,930 --> 00:00:42,875
However, sound waves are, of course, much, much densely sampled.

10
00:00:43,235 --> 00:00:49,461
So these sound waves, they are typically in the order of something like 24 kilohertz sampled.

11
00:00:49,441 --> 00:00:58,019
So that's the ratio of one token to output samples is super high.

12
00:00:58,039 --> 00:01:04,733
So one token will produce many, many thousand samples in the speech.

13
00:01:04,713 --> 00:01:05,997
So that's the first problem.

14
00:01:06,618 --> 00:01:19,735
The second problem is that if you have training data, so you have data that has a piece of text and you have the sound wave that a human, you know the human read that particular piece of text.

15
00:01:19,715 --> 00:01:25,685
You still don't know which word exactly corresponds to which portion of that text.

16
00:01:25,726 --> 00:01:29,132
You simply know the entire text corresponds to the entire sound wave.

17
00:01:29,492 --> 00:01:32,017
You don't know this word text right here.

18
00:01:32,077 --> 00:01:32,578
You don't know.

19
00:01:32,858 --> 00:01:37,386
You don't know where it starts and where it ends in this sound wave.

20
00:01:37,366 --> 00:01:50,222
And the last problem you obviously have is that you want to make this in a way that it generalizes, that it sounds like a human, but also generalizes to some other text.

21
00:01:50,924 --> 00:02:00,049
And this paper here solves all of these problems jointly by doing an adversarial approach to learning.

